<html>
<head>
<title>Bright Side for May 1996 Media Watch</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<center><h2>Bright Side for May 1996 Media Watch</h2></center>
<p>
<h3>NBC: Tough on Criminals?</h3>
<p>
Any suggested link between crime and welfare dependency is usually dismissed by the media as Willie Horton redux. However, Elizabeth Vargas' March 26 Dateline report showed that often welfare money acts as a direct subsidy for scofflaws.
Vargas noted there are "more than 415,000 fugitives on the lam across the country, men and women wanted by the law for serious crimes." After a morning expedition with the Cuyahoga Ohio County Sheriff department, knocking on doors in a fruitless search for a fugitive, she noted that "just a few blocks away from the sheriff's department is all the information those officers say they need. Here in this office are the names, addresses, phone numbers, even photographs, of some of those fugitives from justice. People fleeing from the law but not from the welfare department."
Vargas deftly phrased the irony: "So, while one government agency spends your tax dollars to find fugitives from the law, another government agency gives more of your tax dollars, welfare, to fugitives in hiding." 
After interviewing county welfare director Joseph Garcia claiming the police were on a "fishing expedition" and targeting the poor, Vargas noted that after McFall went public with his battle against federal privacy laws that prevent welfare departments from sharing names and addresses, "deputies are getting some information."
Robert Hager probed the same politically incorrect line in his Fleecing of America report on the April 24 Nightly News. 
Anchor Tom Brokaw introduced the story: "How would you feel if you found out your tax dollars were paying a massive telephone bill for calls that never should have been made, calls coming from prisoners?"
Hager related the General Accounting Office findings of prisoners calling the Agriculture Department -- collect: "652 collect calls accepted from eighteen prisons in all, in just the four months auditors sampled." Hager explained, "The prisoners had found dishonest employees at the Agricultural Department's Washington headquarters, willing to forward on their calls long-distance to whomever the prisoners wanted to talk to, private individuals, anywhere, at taxpayers expense," even calls to sex lines in the Dominican Republic.
<p>
<h3>Stossel on Davis-Bacon</h3>
<p>
In 1931, Congress passed the Davis Bacon Act, prompted by white laborers who were upset that blacks were underbidding them on government contracts. Davis Bacon sets minimum wages for contractors that build government buildings. On the April 12 20/20, ABC's John Stossel looked at how this out-dated government regulation continues to cost taxpayers millions and benefits a major contributor to the Democratic Party: labor unions.
Stossel started at the Labor Department, the agency that enforces Davis Bacon. Stossel explained: "Dozens of them [employees] here, and others in state and city labor departments, spend their time deciding what construction workers on government projects must be paid. The result? Government buildings cost more and poor people who want to work can't." Stossel explained: "Carpenter David Shepherd must get $29 an hour. Normally he makes $15. Sheet metal worker Mike Harley has his pay doubled by the Labor Department."
Stossel explained how the Labor Department uses a complicated formula to issue their wage edicts. In turn, prevailing wages are often set higher than union wages so open-shop contractors can't underbid union shops. Stossel referred to the unions clout: "It is true that the law protects union jobs from cheaper competition. And if a Congressman even discusses changing the law, crowds like this [footage of a congressional hearing with union members] will remind him of the union's clout. Congress' most potent defender of Davis Bacon has been Sen. Edward Kennedy. He declined our request to talk about this."
Stossel went on to point out that while these higher wages may benefit some, there's also a downside for less-skilled laborers. Stossel pointed out: "A side effect of fixing wages is that some workers end up being excluded." At Cabrini Green in Chicago, one of the nation's poorest housing projects, the government is doing repairs. Some construction workers who reside at Cabrini Green would like to be hired to do the work, but as Stossel learned: "They can't get hired because when contractors are forced to pay high Davis Bacon salaries even for the simplest jobs, they're not going to take a chance on inexperienced strangers, they're going to use their most experienced workers."
</blockquote>
</body>
