<html>
<head>
<title>June 1996 MediaWatch</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>

<h2>Verdict: Media Guilty of Apathy--Networks Aggressively Ignored the Crimes of Whitewater</h2><p>

The media elite keeps waiting for Whitewater to end.  "Is this basically the end of
Whitewater?," asked New York Times reporter Linda Greenhouse on PBS's Washington Week in Review
after the First Lady's cattle-futures press conference in 1994. "Whitewater is...sort of
diminishing, sort of fading away," predicted host Ken Bode on the same program on May 24. Just
four days later, Bode and other reporters were embarrassed when the story exploded with 24 fraud
and conspiracy convictions of President Clinton's business partners, Jim and Susan McDougal, and
Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker.

After NBC Nightly News aired only one reporter-based story in the entire three months of the
trial, anchor Tom Brokaw asked Washington Bureau Chief Tim Russert May 28, the night of the
convictions: "Alfonse D'Amato, the Republican Senator who's been running the Whitewater hearings
on Capitol Hill, has so much as admitted recently that he didn't get very far. There have been
any number of exhaustive journalistic efforts. What do we think may be out there? Anything
left?"

On CBS, Dan Rather quickly disposed of "Republican special prosecutor Kenneth Starr" and spent
15 minutes on newly discovered footage surrounding John F. Kennedy's 1963 assassination. When he
returned to the trial, Rather twice insisted "President Clinton was not charged with anything in
this trial." Reporters Scott Pelley (once) and  Rita Braver (twice) repeated that the President
was not a target of investigation. 

The convictions were a stark contrast to the stunning lack of TV coverage of the trial. A
MediaWatch analysis from February 29 to May 28 found the Big Three networks aired only 13
reporter-based Whitewater stories on their evening news shows -- an average of about four
stories per network over three months. (CNN's The World Today reported ten stories.) The three
morning shows also yawned at the story, airing only 14 reporter-based stories and five
interviews during that time. 

Other Clinton scandals continue to be ignored.  On April 5, the Los Angeles Times  broke the
story that the Clinton administration secretly encouraged Iran to send arms to the Bosnian
Muslims while Clinton publicly defended the arms embargo. CBS and NBC have not broadcast a
single evening news story. ABC aired two evening anchor briefs, CNN's The World Today, three.

The networks have yet to touch the May 2 Washington Times story of how Senate Democrats have
placed a hold on a bill reimbursing former White House Travel Office chief Billy Dale for
$500,000 in legal fees -- money he spent defending himself against the Clintons' false charges
that he was an embezzler.<p>
<h2>Setting an Example</h2><p>

While the television networks have been reluctant to cover Whitewater, the print
 media have been
much more thorough. The June 2 Washington Post ran an in-depth, front page story
 on the scandal,
focusing on the role of First Lady Hillary Clinton, concluding that: "Her public
 record suggests
conflicts with self-portrait of naivete."<p>
The nearly five-page story story by David Maraniss and Susan Schmidt looked at t
he conflict
between what Mrs. Clinton has stated and the documented record. While  most of t
he story looked
at the players involved and recounted the entire scandal, the Post prefaced the
story: "The
image is of a mere bystander, a good person victimized. But an examination of Hi
llary Clinton's
public statements suggests someone less passive in her behavior, less consistent
 in her answers,
and less committed to full disclosure than the figure in her self-portrait....He
r wording seems
alternately terse and lawyerly, providing the narrowest possible answers, and un
abashedly
political, ornamented with asides and anecdotes."  <p>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
