<HEAD>
<CENTER><TITLE><b><i>Flash</i></b>: Media Research Center's Monthly Member's Report</TITLE></CENTER>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" 
<U><CENTER><a name="2flash1-6.html"> <font size="8"><I>Tell the Truth!</I> </font size="8"></A>
</B></I> </CENTER></U>
<BR>
<P>On June 5, Media Research Center Chairman Brent Bozell held a national press 
conference in Washington, D.C. to formally announce our $2.8 million<B> "Tell the 
Truth!"</B> campaign to confront and neutralize the anti-conservative bias in the media during the `96 election season.
<P>At the press conference, Bozell told reporters that surveys confirm what some in 
the media are finally admitting. "CBS's 
Bernard Goldberg said it best: `The old argument 
that the networks and other "media elites" have 
a liberal bias is so blatantly true it's hardly worth discussing 
any more.'
<P>"The MRC is not out to prove an anti-conservative bias. That argument is over," 
Bozell stated. "We want to put an end to this 
non-stop onslaught against the conservative movement. 
This campaign demands the media be fair and balanced, period," 
he continued.
<P>Media outlets covering the press conference included 
C-SPAN, CNN, CBN, Reuters, Cox, <I>The</I> <I>Washington 
Post</I>, <I>National Review</I>, <I>Chicago 
Sun-Times</I>, <I>Investor's Business 
Daily</I>, and others.
"Tell the Truth!" is the most ambitious and technologically 
advanced campaign ever devised to confront leftist media bias. 
Based on test-marketing results, we will expose left-wing media bias to an average 
of 50,000 conservative activists and 25 million voters every week. 
<I><B>The media will not get away with distortions or falsehoods this year.</B></I>
<p>
<BR>
<BR>
 <I><CENTER><font size="5">There are nine components to the campaign:</font size="5"></CENTER></I>
<P>
<BR>
<B>1. Research:</B> The cornerstone of all MRC endeavors, the campaign research will 
be compiled by our eight-member media analysis team which tapes and analyzes every 
network newscast, national newspaper, and news magazine to document trends of 
liberal bias. Using the customized MRC Media 
Tracking
 System, the "Tell the Truth!" 
campaign will show the American people <I>exactly 
</I>how the media are distorting the issues -- 
even spiking the news -- in order to promote their pro-Clinton agenda this year.
<P><B>2. Publications:</B> All of the MRC's 
monthly and bi-weekly publications -- 
<I>MediaWatch</I>, <I>MediaNomics</I>, <I>Notable 
Quotables</I>, and <I>Flash </I> -- will focus almost exclusively on the 
issuesand trends of campaign `96, giving thousands of conservative reporters, subscribers, and activists the unique and timely information which they can use as ammunition in their grassroots activism.
<P><B>3. <I>Pattern of Deception</I>:</B><I> </I>MRC 
Associate Editor Tim Graham's new blockbuster book documents the astonishing bias that has 
bolstered the Clinton presidency in the last four years, setting the stage for a national 
discussion of the media's obvious preference for this President. 
<I>Pattern of Deception</I> has already generated great interest among 
the general public, and become one of our best selling publications.
<P><B>4. Talk Radio:</B> Over the past year we 
have quietly established an informal network of over 100 radio talk shows 
-- which includes every major nationally syndicated show -- 
to provide them with up-to-the-minute evidence of left-wing bias masquerading as 
"objective news" in the establishment press. Using MRC material, talk show hosts can now educate millions of voters about the 
ongoing distortion of the "news" media every 
single day. As well, MRC spokesmen are now conducting daily interviews on these shows 
to further expose the liberal media.
<P><B>5. The Internet:</B> Using the Internet, the MRC will be communicating with 
hundreds of thousands of conservative activists 
while simultaneously providing immediate intelligence to the conservative media. The 
MRC website  <a href="http://www.mediaresearch.org">http://www.mediaresearch.org</a> is up and running for public and media 
use during the 1996 campaign, with a full slate of studies, profiles, and Special Reports. In addition, MRC Executive Director Brent Baker is providing "CyberAlerts" through E-mail several times per week to the nation's most influential opinion leaders to facilitate a rapid response to media bias.  
<P><B>6. Media Outreach:</B> Two-page &quot;Media Reality Check '96&quot; rebuttals are 
being sent via &quot;blast fax&quot; to over 1,500 media and political contacts across 
the country on a regular basis. This rapid response technique, honed to 
perfection by the Clinton campaign in 1992, inundated the media with 
counterarguments and rebuttals to anything the Republicans had to say. Now we're 
using it against the leftist media.  
<P><B>7. The National Conventions:</B> During the national conventions, 
the media's left-wing agenda comes shining through. Once again, the MRC 
will be there, publishing a daily newsletter during the two parties' conventions 
to document the ongoing political slant in prime time convention coverage. 
In addition, we will be conducting interviews and press conferences to 
broadcast our findings. This year the MRC is also considering a daily national 
radio feed to provide evidence of reporters' biased coverage. This daily 
commentary will reach tens of millions of voters and activists.
<P><B>8. Conservative Grassroots Activism:</B> To make the so-called 
objective national media an issue in this campaign, the MRC is mass-producing 
and distributing hundreds of thousands of bumper stickers, pens, 
refrigerator magnets, and other novelty items with the tag line &quot;I Don't Believe the 
Liberal News Media.&quot; The national 
distribution efforts are already under way. MRC Members -- 75,000 nationwide -- 
will also participate through letter-writing campaigns and other efforts to 
expose and confront liberal bias at the local level.
<P><B>9. Paid Advertising: </B>The MRC will be advancing its efforts through a 
paid advertising campaign. Conservative newspapers, magazines, and radio 
talk shows will be the vehicles of choice for these efforts. So far the MRC 
has placed several advertisements in <I>Human 
Events</I> and the <I>Washington Times Weekly</I>, and we will be buying 
advertisements in <I>National Review</I> and 
<I>The American Spectator</I>. Funds permitting, ads will air on radio and television 
as well.<BR>
<br>
<br>

<b><i><center><a href="flas1-6.html">"Flash"</a></center></i></b>
